				<div class="row">
					<div class="col-md-3 col-md-offset-2 text-left">
						<p class="hm2">
							<strong><a href="http://www.ctod.org/pdfs/tod101.pdf" target="_blank">TOD 101: Why TOD? Why Now?</a></strong>
						</p>
					</br>
						<p class="hm2">
						The first in a series of short publications on TOD funded by the Federal Transit Administration.  In an easy-to-read format, concisely explains what TOD is and how shifting demographics and a changing real estate market have increased TOD opportunities. (2007, 24 pp.)
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="col-md-3 col-md-offset-0 text-left">
						<br>
						<a href="http://www.ctod.org/pdfs/tod101.pdf" target="_blank"><img src="img/tod101.png" class="img-responsive" alt="Image Title"></a>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="row">
					<div class="col-md-3 col-md-offset-2 text-left">
						<p class="hm2">
							<strong><a href="http://www.ctod.org/pdfs/tod202stations.pdf" target="_blank">TOD 202: Station Area Planning</strong></a>
						</p>
					</br>
						<p class="hm2">
						Part of a series on TOD funded by the Federal Transit Administration, TOD 202 aims to simplify the complex decisions that surround planning for TOD projects and station areas.  Following the easy-to-read format of TOD 101, this manual provides details about the scales of development likely to occur in different places, offers insights into station area planning principles, and includes TOD plan checklists. (2008, 28 pp.)
						</p>
					</div>
					<br>
					<div class="col-md-3 col-md-offset-0 text-left">
						<a href="http://www.ctod.org/pdfs/tod202stations.pdf" target="_blank"><img src="img/tod202.png" class="img-responsive" alt="Image Title"></a>
					</div>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="row">
					<div class="col-md-3 col-md-offset-2 text-left">
						<br>
						<p class="hm2">
							<strong><a href="http://www.fta.dot.gov/documents/TOD_Lessons_Learned_12_21.pdf" target="_blank">FTA's TOD Lessons Learned</strong></a>
						</p>
					</br>
						<p class="hm2">
						This short booklet summarizes the results of listening sessions undertaken by the Federal Transit Administration (FTA) in several cities with new or impending transit investments. Input from planners, developers, and bankers in Portland, Minneapolis, Phoenix, and Charlotte, is distilled into a summary of what works, what doesn’t work, and what facilitates successful TOD.  (2005, 12 pp.)
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="col-md-3 col-md-offset-0 text-left">
						<br>
						<a href="http://www.fta.dot.gov/documents/TOD_Lessons_Learned_12_21.pdf" target="_blank"><img src="img/fta.png" class="img-responsive" alt="Image Title"></a>
					</div>
					<p>
				</div>
				<br>
				<div class="row">
					<div class="col-md-3 col-md-offset-2 text-left">
						<p class="hm2">
							<a href="http://uli.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/TP_DevTransit.ashx_.pdf" target="_blank"><strong>ULI's Ten Principles for Successful Development Around Transit</strong></a>
						</p>
					</br>
						<p class="hm2">
						A concise overview of ten principles for successful TODs, published by land use research organization Urban Land Institute. Intended as “reminders” for communities, designers, developers, and transit agencies working to create TOD, this booklet draws on many examples from around the country to illustrate the principles it outlines. (2003, 23 pp.)
						</p>
